  <h4>Inline</h4>
  <p>Inline alerts can be placed in a container or component and should not obstruct other content. The required elements are a thin top bar or thin border, icon, title, and a container background. Supporting text that provides more clarity about the alert message severity may or may not be included below the title.</p>

  {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-style-inline.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component, inline" style="--example-img-max-width: 538px;">
  {%- endcall %}

  <h4>Inline, alternate</h4>
  <p>The alternate Inline alert style includes a border instead of a top line which is used to express more urgency or grab the attention of a user.</p>

    {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-style-inline-alt.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component, inline alternate" style="--example-img-max-width: 538px;">
  {%- endcall %}

  <h4>Toast</h4>
  <p>Toast alerts slide into view from the top right corner of the page and rest on top of any content underneath. The required elements are a thin top bar, icon, title, close button, and a white container with a subtle drop shadow. Supporting text that provides more clarity about the alert message severity may or may not be included below the title.</p>

  {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-style-toast.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component, toast" style="--example-img-max-width: 538px;">
  {%- endcall %}

{%- endcall %}

{% call components.section("Usage") -%}

  <p>Alerts are notifications that appear or are generated to communicate with users or attract their attention.</p>

  <h4>Inline</h4>
  <p>Inline alerts are used to present simple information or a local notification, like after a user submits a form with errors. Inline alerts should be informational or identify any actions that are required before a user can continue, therefore they should have the option to be dismissed.<p>

  <h4>Toast</h4>
  <p>Toast alerts are used to present a notification about an important global event or change. They should notify a user, not interrupt their experience, therefore they should have the option to be dismissed.</p>

  <h4>Severity</h4>
  <p>Severity communicates the <em>urgency</em> of an alert. The combination of a status icon, title, and container styling all help to clarify the various severity levels of alerts.</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Default</strong> - Use to indicate generic information or a message with no severity.</li>
    <li><strong>Info</strong> - Use to indicate helpful information or a message with little to no severity.</li>
    <li><strong>Success</strong> - Use to indicate a success state, like if a process was completed without errors.</li>
    <li><strong>Warning</strong> - Use to indicate a caution state, like a non-blocking error that might need to be fixed.</li>
    <li><strong>Danger</strong> - Use to indicate a danger state, like an error that is blocking a user from completing a task.</li>
  </ul>

  {% call components.example(palette='light') %}
    <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-severity.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component severity" style="--example-img-max-width: 728px;">
  {%- endcall %}

{%- endcall %}

{% call components.section("Positioning") -%}

  <h4>Inline</h4>
  <p>Inline alerts should be placed toward the top of a container or component and will push other content down. Inline alerts have no fixed width, they conform to the width of the container they are placed in and will persist until a user dismisses them or navigates away from the page.</p>

  <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-positioning-inline.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component positioning, inline">

  <h4>Toast</h4>
  <p>Toast alerts slide in from the top right edge of the screen and overlay content. They have a fixed width of six grid columns on <strong>large screens</strong> and they persist until they time out after five seconds or when a user dismisses them.</p>

  <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-positioning-toast.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component positioning, toast">

{%- endcall %}

{% call components.section("Behavior") -%}

  <h4>Stacking</h4>
  <p>When multiple Toast alerts are triggered, they will stack on top of each other. The most recent alert is placed at the top of the stack and push the other alerts down. When stacked Toast alerts are dismissed by a user or time out, the remaining alerts will slide up and fill the empty space.</p>

  <img src="{{ '/assets/alert/alert-behavior.svg' | url }}" alt="Alert component behavior">

{%- endcall %}

